{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-lifecycle"') }}
  <h3 id="how-it-works">Lifecycle Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    An entity never bundles its workflow rules. It declares a <strong>lifecycle definition</strong> (status
    set + transition map), resolves the application's <strong>lifecycle provider</strong> through the
    injector chain, and asks it to fire a transition. The provider evaluates the edge's guard (delegating
    authorization to a guard provider), applies the move, and emits the transition event. The protocol fixes
    only the seam &mdash; the engine behind the provider is swappable.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// The transition map — the ONLY lock. Data-defined, so it is portable across engines.
interface LifecycleDefinition<S extends string> {
  initial: S;
  states: Record<S, { terminal?: boolean }>;
  transitions: Array<{
    from: S; to: S;
    // Authorization is NOT owned here — `guard` names a Web Guards predicate the
    // CustomGuardProvider resolves (async, server-authoritative). Omit for an unguarded move.
    guard?: string;
    // The role permitted to fire it (a UX hint; the guard provider is the real gate). Omit = automatic.
    actor?: string;
  }>;
}

// The provider seam — satisfied by the native default and every plugged engine alike.
interface CustomLifecycleProvider<S extends string = string> {
  // Which transitions are currently available to this actor (guards pre-evaluated).
  available(entity: EntityRef, actor: ActorRef): Promise<S[]>;
  // Fire one. Rejects if the edge is unknown or its guard denies. On success, emits the event.
  transition(entity: EntityRef, to: S, actor: ActorRef): Promise<LifecycleEvent<S>>;
}

interface LifecycleEvent<S extends string> {
  entity: EntityRef; from: S; to: S; actor: ActorRef; at: string; // ISO
}

// 1. The application registers ONE provider (native-first default; project overrides it).
customLifecycles.define('loan', new XStateLifecycleProvider(loanDefinition));

injector Application {
  provide { lifecycle: 'loan' } to '@web-lifecycle';   // every descendant resolves this provider
}

// 2. A surface delegates — it owns neither the rules nor the authorization.
const provider = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(el, 'customLifecycles');
const next = await provider.available(loan, currentUser);     // → ['underwriting', 'declined']
const ev = await provider.transition(loan, 'underwriting', currentUser); // guard-checked + audited
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>One contract:</strong> <code>CustomLifecycleProvider</code> &mdash;
      <code>available()</code> + <code>transition()</code> &mdash; is satisfied by the default and every
      plugged workflow engine alike.</li>
    <li><strong>One registry:</strong> <code>CustomLifecycleRegistry</code>
      (<code>window.customLifecycles</code>) holds the named definitions/providers; the project selects or
      overrides via the injector chain.</li>
    <li><strong>Authorization is delegated, never re-implemented:</strong> a transition's
      <code>guard</code> is a <a href="/projects/webguards/">Web Guards</a> predicate resolved by the
      <code>CustomGuardProvider</code> &mdash; async, server-authoritative, the front-end is a UX mirror.
      Web Lifecycle owns <em>the state machine</em>; Web Guards owns <em>who may fire an edge</em>.</li>
    <li><strong>Every transition is observable:</strong> the emitted <code>LifecycleEvent</code> is the
      composition seam for audit-trail (<a href="/backlog/357-audit-trail-standard/">#357</a>) and reporting
      &mdash; the standard does not own the log, only the event.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="composition"') }}
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/status-indicator/">Status Indicator intent</a></strong> &mdash; the UX half:
      the canonical chip/badge for the current state plus the available next transitions. It reads the same
      provider; it is the lifecycle's visual member.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webguards/">Web Guards</a></strong> &mdash; resolves each transition's
      guard predicate (authorization / precondition). Web Lifecycle declares <em>which</em> guard an edge
      needs; Web Guards decides it.</li>
    <li><strong>Audit-trail (<a href="/backlog/357-audit-trail-standard/">#357</a>)</strong> &mdash; consumes
      the transition event to build the immutable per-entity history.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webstates/">Web States</a></strong> &mdash; the entity's current status is
      reactive state; a status change is a Change Record. Web Lifecycle adds the <em>legal-move</em> layer
      on top of the primitive.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="status"') }}
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Lifecycle is in <strong>concept</strong> phase; the Lifecycle protocol's seam (status set +
    transition map + provider + event) is specified here at <strong>draft</strong>. It was surfaced by the
    loan-origination exercise app (<a href="/backlog/317-exercise-app-loan-origination/">#317</a>), whose
    application moves through exactly this guarded, role-scoped machine. The native-first default provider
    and a reference runtime block (to make that app conformant) are the first planned work, on top of this
    contract.
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>Does the definition carry side-effects (on-enter / on-exit actions), or stay purely declarative and
      leave effects to the consumer subscribing to the event?</li>
    <li>Parallel / nested states (statechart regions) &mdash; in scope, or explicitly flat-only for v1?</li>
    <li>How does an <em>automatic</em> transition (no actor, fired by a condition) express its trigger &mdash;
      a guard that returns "fire", or a separate scheduler concern?</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}
